{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5ed98e40-38b3-40de-ac5e-79f237701fb6","content":"To switch from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you just need to **remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property in your project file:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Before -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n\n<!-- After -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Why this is enough:** Starting with MSTest.Sdk 3.4+, Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the **default** runner. Setting `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` was explicitly opting out of it. Removing that property (or setting it to `false`) switches you back to the default.\n\n**Key behavioral differences to be aware of:**\n\n1. **CLI output** — Test results display inline in the terminal by default (no separate `.trx` needed).\n2. **Running tests** — Use `dotnet test` as before, but you can also run the test project directly (`dotnet run`) or use `--` to pass platform-specific options (e.g., `dotnet test -- --filter \"Name=MyTest\"`).\n3. **CI/TRX reports** — If you need `.trx` output, add `dotnet test --results-directory ./results -- --report-trx`.\n4. **VS Test Explorer** — Works normally; no changes needed.\n\nThat single property removal is the only required change.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"00b9d8f0-f502-44ba-861a-da2c811d28df","outputTokens":366,"requestId":"5C3C:F5EE8:9FECB:C92F3:69F54AED"},"id":"39983dc8-30ff-4dc3-b6f5-fe7fe8d8369b","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:53:12.562Z","parentId":"6376c1f6-f7ea-4e08-94a9-cb849b809428"}
